WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.840
- We all know you.

00:00:00.840 --> 00:00:01.660
- I know, I know.

00:00:01.660 --> 00:00:04.380
Okay, so I'm gonna talk about chemo-less,

00:00:04.380 --> 00:00:06.920
not chemo-free approaches for elderly patients

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:08.840
with newly diagnosed large-term lymphoma.

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:11.740
I was giving this talk because we have a trial concept

00:00:11.740 --> 00:00:12.860
in startup at UCLA.

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:14.760
That's what I'm gonna talk about,

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:15.940
but that's the last slide.

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:19.320
So we have to get through the other ones to get there.

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:20.600
So what do we know?

00:00:21.560 --> 00:00:23.580
Jörn Chapuis' data at ASH,

00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:27.780
the r-polar-glow combination chemo,

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:29.900
not quite chemo-free, it's chemo-mini,

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.020
in newly diagnosed elderly patients

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:37.120
not deemed to be candidates for full-dose chemo.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:40.900
Those data represented at ASH were quite impressive.

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:44.840
So patients receive six cycles of combination

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:49.020
polar glufidamab and rituxan.

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:52.520
And then after six cycles, they continue for another 12,

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:54.440
for a total of 12 cycles of glufidamab

00:00:54.440 --> 00:00:58.480
for a total of 12-month, 12-cycle treatment course.

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:03.380
And for principle to the left,

00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:05.980
patient with a lot of disease within two weeks

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:08.100
of this Vegemin achieved a complete remission.

00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:10.580
That was nice to see.

00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:12.580
And if you see on the right,

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:15.120
these are data at post-cycle two,

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:17.680
post-cycle six, and post-cycle 12.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:22.680
The CR rates started to improve from 58 to 81%.

00:01:22.900 --> 00:01:24.780
And also at the bottom on the right,

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:28.340
you see the relapses started to occur as well.

00:01:28.340 --> 00:01:29.600
So, but those data were rather,

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:33.620
rather striking for an almost chemo free regimen

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:36.420
for a patient with aggressive diffuse HB cell lymphoma.

00:01:38.420 --> 00:01:41.240
And of course we need more follow-up to know

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:43.040
if these responses are durable,

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:44.600
but the one-year progression-free survival,

00:01:44.600 --> 00:01:47.280
one-year overall survival rates as shown here,

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:51.040
I look really, really good with 84 and 90,

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:56.040
89% overall survival rate.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:01:59.400
So how about,

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:01.900
what do you think about the tolerability?

00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:06.900
So on the left patient had a grade three infection, 19%.

00:02:07.220 --> 00:02:08.560
Three patients died.

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:13.340
Mainly COVID was blamed for that, one was unknown.

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:16.880
And if you look about infections over time,

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:19.500
they had activity in the beginning of the first cycle,

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:21.320
then kind of tapered off.

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:23.980
But I think we have to keep an eye

00:02:23.980 --> 00:02:27.740
on the follow-up infectious complications far on the right.

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:31.440
Seem to pile up infections there,

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:33.020
but of course the more time you wait,

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:34.700
the more you collect.

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:40.420
But I think we'll need to see how doable the efficacy is

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:45.420
and how much side effects we get with infections over time.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:53.720
How about Epcotamab plus our mini CHOP for elderly patients?

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:57.000
Those data were shown at ASH as well.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Here it was time limited course, six,

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.060
six cycles of combination where Epcot and mini CHOP

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:04.980
was being given from the get-go.

00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:07.320
And then the cycle seven, cycle eight,

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:09.940
monotherapy with Epcotamab, and then the treatment stops.

00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:13.580
So this combination therapy, shorter time course,

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:17.460
again, elderly patients not deemed candidates

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:19.420
for aggressive full dose CHOP.

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:24.500
And so the overall response rates and CRR rates

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:28.800
were what you expected, they looked great, 86% CRR.

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:31.700
CRR rates, 93% overall response rate.

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:34.620
And we'll have to see what the longer follow-up will show.

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:37.380
In terms of, and that's progressively survival,

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:38.780
overall survival data here,

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:44.360
what you would expect in terms of safety,

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:46.420
there was no surprises.

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:50.780
Actually, CRS rates were low, grade one, grade two,

00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:53.140
maybe being protected.

00:03:53.140 --> 00:03:56.940
Patients, when you give five days of steroids

00:03:56.940 --> 00:03:58.600
and chemotherapy at the same time that you,

00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:02.860
administer bispecifics, some neutropenia, but not too much.

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:06.660
That's all kind of side effects that one would expect

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:08.860
in this patient population, no surprises there.

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:15.420
And again, CRS, as you would see with single agent

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:20.420
bispecifics, you see the uptake of CRS

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:23.840
with the first full dose, which is at cycle one, day 15,

00:04:23.840 --> 00:04:25.740
mainly grade one, grade two events.

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:33.400
So this was very surprising data to me.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:37.340
And we have seen more of this early this morning,

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:41.120
the morning sun data, mozutuzumab for elderly patients.

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:44.100
These patients only received a time-limited course

00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:47.140
of mozutuzumab for newly diagnosed diffusor,

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:48.600
Spitzel, and for many progression-free

00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:51.400
and over survival data, look rather promising.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.320
Of course, the follow-up is short,

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:57.340
but I do have two patients that run this trial.

00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:01.520
One of them, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:04.320
and the second patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:06.540
and the third patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:08.540
and the fourth patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:08.540 --> 00:05:09.540
and the fifth patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:10.540
and the sixth patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:11.540
and the fifth patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:12.540
and the sixth patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:13.540
and the seventh patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:14.540
and the sixth patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:15.540
and the seventh patient, who had been in a coma for more than a year,

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:23.520
right now. So I want to take advantage of the intact immune system, giving biospecifics without

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:30.480
giving anything else that inhibits them first. So patients receive two cycles of epcridomab

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:35.560
in order to make this more palatable in terms of side effects. And they get one dose of Polar,

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:40.960
one dose of Rituxan prior to that. A little bit of tumour debulking, but also getting rid of

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:46.860
circulating B-cells to some degree to diminish the side effect risk. And then patients with

00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:53.220
cycle three continue with epcridomab, but we dial in Polar mini-CHP.

00:05:54.740 --> 00:06:01.420
And if patients achieve a complete remission after two cycles of the culmination of

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:09.760
Polar mini-CHP and epcridomab, so it's cycle four total, then we have the option of stopping the

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:10.760
chemo-containing.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:20.660
If a patient's lymphoma grows right through epcridomab in the first two cycles, we can start

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:28.920
the Polar mini-CHP at any point. And we will have serial MRD testing along the way to inform us

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:34.980
about the speed of tumour burden response by MRD testing through collaboration.

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:41.180
And yeah, I said that. So if we have the option of not only,

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:49.680
reducing the amount of chemotherapy we're giving with a mini CHP approach, but also reducing the

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:58.240
amount of chemotherapy cycles we administer. So the idea, therefore, is to emphasise immunotherapy

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:03.920
and de-emphasise chemotherapy and find just the right dose of chemotherapy, not too much and not

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:09.360
too little. And finding the right balance between time-limited effective treatment and also avoiding

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:11.180
open-ended immunotherapy with Prozac. So that's the first step. The second step is to find the

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:15.060
potentially toxicities and that was it.
